John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continues in 2018 with another set of exceptional test scores, which is bolstered by individual and group success in sport, the arts, music and other areas of community performance.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, careers of their choice and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that is able to design and incorporate a personalised curriculum, we find that modern languages continue to gain popularity as a sought-after area of study in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a person in a language they understand, it goes into their head.
If you talk to a man in his own language, it goes to his heart".
This is an important reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of the last tests this year, you can see that languages are at the top of the charts with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved high A's.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved high A's in Mandarin, as did 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish.
These data show that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, the field of languages as an elective is considered to be on the same level as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Council found that among the reasons employers cited for coding to fill vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a vital requirement to prepare students for future careers.
Given the increasing demand for languages for future job opportunities, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career a person chooses, if he learns a second language, he will have a significant advantage in the future because of this lifelong ability.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically puts a person in a position of advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language at a level sufficient for conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage of speakers, 15 percent.
That's why it's important to invest in language teaching for children today.
Knowledge of many languages, especially those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different in the languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will teach languages considered most important for Britain looking ahead to the 21st century, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
No matter what the child's field of interest is, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in independent schools, with a team of teachers who specialize in the field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, in any foreseeable future.
It cannot be denied that today, in a global business environment, languages continue to be vital to the future of a country, and so this fact must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages are to be seen as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer these levels of choice, diversity and excellence to the children of Scotland.
It's the order of the hour.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
